{
  "answer": "**In *Traité de la propriété* Vol. I, Charles Comte establishes occupation by indigenous or \"savage\" peoples (e.g., tribes in America) as a legitimate basis for territorial property, albeit one that civilized nations may dispute due to the former's failure to develop the land through industry.**[^1][^2] He notes that such hordes claim exclusive territories (hunting grounds, pastures) predating recorded history, treating violations as existential threats that provoke fierce wars.[^3] However, their sparse use of vast lands leaves room for conquest by more productive peoples, as seen in the U.S. example where Anglo-American industry transformed \"a vast forest traversed by a few savage tribes\" into valuable properties.[^4]\n\n**Vol. II (Ch. 44) introduces the key nuance: even lands usurped from indigenous peoples via conquest become fully guaranteed properties over time through long, peaceful possession (prescription), as no better title emerges and society prioritizes stability.**[^5] Comte explicitly references his Vol. I analysis of *legitimate* formation via occupation/industry, clarifying it did not exhaust reality—usurpations (e.g., conquests replacing prior occupants) routinely occur and receive legal protection once consolidated, lest universal insecurity ensue.[^6] Vol. I had omitted this stabilizing mechanism: how illegitimate acquisitions from \"savage hordes\" transition to protected titles, as families die out, lands regenerate value under new owners, and prescription (often ~30 years, akin to a human lifespan) bars reclamation.[^7]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, Ch. 4 \"De l'occupation des choses\" [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/#p-ab8596).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, Ch. 7 \"Du territoire propre à chaque nation\" [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/07-du-territoire-propre-a-chaque-nation/translation/#p-53c102).\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, Ch. 7 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/07-du-territoire-propre-a-chaque-nation/translation/#p-0178a5).\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, Ch. 7 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/07-du-territoire-propre-a-chaque-nation/translation/#p-0a6e26).\n[^5]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL II*, Ch. 44 \"De la garantie donnée aux possesseurs des biens acquis par usurpation\" [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5/44-de-la-garantie-donnee-aux-possesseurs-des-biens-ac/translation/#p-64a879).\n[^6]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL II*, Ch. 44 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5/44-de-la-garantie-donnee-aux-possesseurs-des-biens-ac/translation/#p-7877a1).\n[^7]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL II*, Ch. 44 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5/44-de-la-garantie-donnee-aux-possesseurs-des-biens-ac/translation/#p-27c176).",
